🚀 Day 5 of Deep Learning Journey: — Training the Perceptron & Understanding the Perceptron Trick 🎯
Today I focused on one of the most important parts of neural networks — how the perceptron actually learns, i.e., how it finds the correct values of weights (w) and bias (b).
🧠 Key concepts I learned:
🔹 How Perceptron Training Works
 The perceptron starts with random weights and bias, which means the initial decision boundary (line) is also random. From there, it improves step by step by correcting mistakes.
🔹 Perceptron Trick (Core Idea)
 Whenever the model makes a wrong prediction:
 • It identifies the misclassified data point
 • Then it adjusts the weights and bias in a way that moves the decision boundary closer to correct classification
This process keeps repeating for many iterations (called epochs, e.g., 1000 times), gradually improving the model.
🔹 Geometric Intuition
 The decision boundary is a line:
 w1·x1 + w2·x2 + b = 0
If a point is on the wrong side of the line:
 • The algorithm shifts the line by updating coefficients (w1, w2, b)
 • This shift ensures the wrongly classified point moves to the correct side
🔹 Update Rule (Most Important Insight)
 The perceptron updates weights using:
 w = w + learning_rate × (y − ŷ) × x
Where:
 • y = actual value
 • ŷ = predicted value
 • x = input features
 • learning_rate = controls how big the update step is
🔹 Learning Rate
 The learning rate decides how fast the model learns:
 • Small value → slow but stable learning
 • Large value → faster but can overshoot
🔹 Algorithm Understanding (from code)
 • Insert bias term into input
 • Initialize weights to zero
 • For multiple epochs:
 - Pick a random data point
 - Predict output
 - Update weights if prediction is wrong
This iterative correction process is what allows the perceptron to learn the optimal decision boundary.
🔹 Visualization Insight
 By running this process over many epochs (like 1000), you can actually see the decision boundary adjusting step by step until it separates the classes correctly.
💡 Key Takeaway:
 Today made it clear that learning in neural networks is nothing but repeated error correction. The perceptron doesn’t “know” the answer initially — it learns by continuously adjusting itself based on mistakes.
